The whole inland state of Bolivia has still freshened in memory the coastline they lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 1800s, and the country longs for once again to sail in the Pacific.
These hopes may be greater than they have been in decades, awaiting a judgment from the International Court of Justice on 1 October after five years of discussion.
“Bolivia has a driving force, a community spirit and a calm mind, and of course awaits the outcome with a positive attitude”, said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the judgment of the International Court on a large screen in many different parts of the country, hoping that the Hague Court will give its judgment in favour of Bolivia’s claim that Chile – after several decades of sporadic negotiations – is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia its own expiration to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic native president – who faces a controversial re-election campaign next year – has also put a great deal on Monday’s decision.
“We are very close to a return to the Pacific,” he promised late in August.
However, some analysts believe that the court will hardly take Bolivia’s side and that very little would change if it had.
The UN body, which belongs to the Netherlands, has no authority to allow them to give away Chilean rural areas and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
That the judgment of the International Court comes only six months after the last arguments were heard indicates that the case “is not complicated”, according to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
