“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” said Zárate.
She believes that Morales' antagonist rhetoric has wiped away any remaining kindness on Chile's side.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the negotiations at one point or another, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the matter after that.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative at the Hague, rejected the theory that the court’s decision came unusually quickly.
According to him, Monday will give Bolivia “an exceptional opportunity to open a new generation of relations with Chile” and the possibility to “stop 139 years of disagreement, in favour of both parties”.
Calzadilla also refused that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – has used the maritime situation as a political shelf.
