Update of algae flowering: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the FWC of the Florida Fisheries and Animal Life Commission shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the FWC, spot - inspiring blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County — suggesting reduced concentrations.
A bloom of red algers stretches around 210 km along the coast, from north of Pinellas to south of Lee County.
There are spots around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than last week.
Red algae has also been observed in Pasco County.
It has been reported to mean large concentrations at or outside the coast of Pinellas County in the last week, low to high concentrations outside the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations at or outside the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations at or outside the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
No respiratory irritation was reported in the northwestern Florida during the last week.
